        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2229632697" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13189219215302874685">This was an excellent Cadfael. Perhaps my favorite in the series. <br/><br/>Many great questions were brought up in this little mystery! What was heresy in 12th century England? What are some of the motivations for accusing someone of heresy and are they always strictly about the church or can they be more personal? Can a &quot;former heretic&quot; (even if he was one unwittingly for 2min, 7 years ago) be buried on Abbey lands? I was able to sit in on a few doctrinal discussions in the Abbey as some of these points</span>
  <span id="freeText13189219215302874685" style="display:none">This was an excellent Cadfael. Perhaps my favorite in the series. <br /><br />Many great questions were brought up in this little mystery! What was heresy in 12th century England? What are some of the motivations for accusing someone of heresy and are they always strictly about the church or can they be more personal? Can a "former heretic" (even if he was one unwittingly for 2min, 7 years ago) be buried on Abbey lands? I was able to sit in on a few doctrinal discussions in the Abbey as some of these points were debated as "The Heretic's Apprentice," named Elave was tried for heresy.<br /><br />Excellent mystery and excellent peek into this topic of heresy!</span>
