<div id="review_1238104739" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1238104739" />
    <a title="Deborah Pickstone" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37849334-deborah-pickstone"><img alt="Deborah Pickstone" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432503842p2/37849334.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1238104739?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deborah Pickstone" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deborah Pickstone" href="/user/show/37849334-deborah-pickstone">Deborah Pickstone</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=favourite-authors">favourite-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=welsh-history">welsh-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=serieses-fictional">serieses-fictional</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=makes-me-think">makes-me-think</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=uk-fiction">uk-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=human-nature">human-nature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=all-time-faves">all-time-faves</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=history-of-all-things">history-of-all-things</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=medieval">medieval</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37849334-deborah-pickstone?shelf=stop-police">stop-police</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1238104739" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8893406672717904653">Satisfying re-read of an old favourite. I was particularly taken, on this read, by the interesting subject matter of heresy. Of course, it all came out well but yet an overview of the possible positions that might be taken on the subject were examined and the peril that such an accusation placed a person in at that time made clear. Although Cadfael is very much HF comfort reading, it is clear the Ellis Peters (Edith Pargeter) actually was well-read on the subject (which is one I find most intere</span>
  <span id="freeText8893406672717904653" style="display:none">Satisfying re-read of an old favourite. I was particularly taken, on this read, by the interesting subject matter of heresy. Of course, it all came out well but yet an overview of the possible positions that might be taken on the subject were examined and the peril that such an accusation placed a person in at that time made clear. Although Cadfael is very much HF comfort reading, it is clear the Ellis Peters (Edith Pargeter) actually was well-read on the subject (which is one I find most interesting) and drew out the point that even the Augustinian conformist position at the time was not the sole position Augustine ever took. It is another example of the victor writing history - or, in this case, prescribing the acceptable theological norm, rendering all other though heretical - erroneous. Myself, I have a liking for the so-called Pelagian 'heresy' and very much agreed with the tale's protagonist that the notion of unbaptised babies being damned and born in original sin is frankly barking - but those were the positions at the time - Augustine was not noted for being easy-going! He asserted that human beings could not attain righteousness by their own efforts and were totally dependent upon the grace of God. So - no free will and cut no slack.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8893406672717904653" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


