    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2529832953" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2529832953" />
    <a title="Nancy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108416-nancy"><img alt="Nancy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1351512283p2/108416.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2529832953?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy" href="/user/show/108416-nancy">Nancy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108416-nancy?shelf=historical">historical</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2529832953" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8606480558035416407">Well-written historical fiction is an opportunity to time-travel and this Ellis Peters novel plunked me so deeply in the Church of the Middle Ages that I was examining my belief system as I read. And, I was nervous about my casual acceptance of my faith and how it would be perceived by the Church hierarchy (if examined).<br/><br/>THE HERETIC&apos;S APPRENTICE showcased both the simplicity, complexity, and dangers that can be associated with religious belief during periods when the institution(s) feel threatene</span>
  <span id="freeText8606480558035416407" style="display:none">Well-written historical fiction is an opportunity to time-travel and this Ellis Peters novel plunked me so deeply in the Church of the Middle Ages that I was examining my belief system as I read. And, I was nervous about my casual acceptance of my faith and how it would be perceived by the Church hierarchy (if examined).<br /><br />THE HERETIC'S APPRENTICE showcased both the simplicity, complexity, and dangers that can be associated with religious belief during periods when the institution(s) feel threatened. I didn't see the focus on the danger resulting from one man's thoughtless conversation as an indictment of the Church, but more an exposition of the dangers of zealotry, the fear of those potentially facing loss of social or political power, and the helplessness of those caught in the wake.<br /><br />Peters is so gifted in describing her world that the reader can not help but take away some understanding of the life in Brother Cadfael's world. For those readers who are not acquainted with the tales of this (more worldly than most) monk, it is always a learning experience to follow his adventures---whether we are gaining bits of knowledge about herbal healing, bookbinding, or The Crusades, we leave these books with something more than just a few hours entertainment. And THE HERETIC'S APPRENTICE was a particularly good chapter in this series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8606480558035416407" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

